expertise_classifications.author: robobun
expertise_signals: Identifies a use-after-free / dangling pointer bug: delete without nullifying the pointer
Understands C++ memory management pitfall where a deleted pointer must be set to nullptr to prevent double-free or dangling access
Targets the exact correct location in cleanup logic (clearAll function)
expertise_classifications.summary: Fixes a dangling pointer bug by setting virtualModules to nullptr after deletion in the plugin clear function, showing understanding of C++ memory safety patterns but requiring minimal code change.

expertise_classifications.author: chrislloyd
expertise_signals: Understands JSC VM internals: uses vm.propertyNames->disposeSymbol to correctly wire up Symbol.dispose at the prototype level
Reuses the existing mockRestore function reference from the prototype rather than creating a new function, avoiding unnecessary allocations
Correctly sets PropertyAttribute::Function | PropertyAttribute::DontEnum to match expected symbol property semantics
Tests cover multiple usage patterns (spyOn with object methods, mock() standalone, prototype methods) and verify auto-restore behavior via `using` blocks
expertise_classifications.summary: Adds Symbol.dispose support to mock/spyOn by wiring mockRestore as the dispose handler at the JSC prototype level, demonstrating understanding of JSC VM internals, property attribute semantics, and the TC39 explicit resource management proposal.

expertise_classifications.author: cirospaciari
expertise_signals: Precisely separates CONNECT tunnel mode from proxy-style absolute URLs (http://...) in the HTTP parser, understanding that the previous code incorrectly grouped them together causing the parser to enter tunnel mode for non-CONNECT requests
Understands the low-level HTTP parser state machine in C++ (HttpParser.h) and the subtle distinction between CONNECT method semantics vs proxy-style request targets per RFC 7230
Tests enforce keep-alive with maxSockets:1 to reproduce the specific hang condition where tunnel mode on a reused connection would block subsequent requests
Comprehensive test coverage including mixed normal/proxy-style URLs, POST with bodies, and sequential requests on the same connection — targeting the exact failure scenario
expertise_classifications.summary: Fixes a bug where proxy-style absolute URLs (e.g., GET http://example.com/path) incorrectly triggered tunnel mode in the HTTP parser (intended only for CONNECT), causing subsequent keep-alive requests to hang — demonstrating deep understanding of HTTP parsing state transitions and connection reuse semantics.

expertise_classifications.author: sosukesuzuki
expertise_signals: Implements int32 fast path with separate adjustSliceOffsetInt32 vs adjustSliceOffsetDouble functions, showing awareness of JSC's value representation and avoiding unnecessary double conversions in the hot path
Correctly handles edge cases: NaN → 0, negative indices clamped to 0, detached buffers, resizable/growable shared buffers with std::nullopt length, and null buffer checks
Moves implementation from JS builtins to native C++ using the IDLOperation pattern consistent with existing JSBuffer methods, demonstrating understanding of the Bun binding architecture
Properly manages JSC throwScope with RETURN_IF_EXCEPTION and RELEASE_AND_RETURN macros, handles byteOffset accumulation for subarrays correctly (byteOffset + startOffset)
expertise_classifications.summary: Moves Buffer.slice/subarray from JavaScript builtins to native C++ with an int32 fast path, demonstrating deep understanding of JSC internals, TypedArray semantics (including resizable buffers and detached state), and the Bun native binding patterns.

expertise_classifications.author: dylan-conway
expertise_signals: Built a complete JSON5 parser from scratch in Zig (913-line interchange/json5.zig) with proper handling of Unicode escapes, hex/infinity/NaN literals, single-line and multi-line comments, trailing commas, and unquoted keys

Integrated the new parser deeply across the entire stack: module loader, bundler linker, parse tasks, transpiler, DevServer watch store, JS bindings, and type definitions — showing comprehensive understanding of Bun's architecture

Exposed the parser through a well-designed Bun.JSON5 API that mirrors JSON semantics (parse with reviver, stringify with replacer/space) while properly bridging Zig and JavaScript via JSValue bindings

Comprehensive test suite with 1573+ lines of unit tests plus a generated JSON5 test suite (934 lines), covering edge cases like Unicode code points, nested comments, special float values, and error recovery
expertise_classifications.summary: Implements a complete native JSON5 parser in Zig and integrates it across Bun's entire compilation pipeline (module loader, bundler, transpiler, JS API bindings, and type definitions), demonstrating architect-level understanding of the runtime's architecture and cross-cutting concerns.

expertise_classifications.author: dylan-conway
expertise_signals: Renamed CatchScope to TopExceptionScope across 71 files, tracking an upstream WebKit API rename with surgical precision
Added bmalloc.lib linking requirement on Windows, indicating understanding of WebKit's memory allocator architecture changes
Changed USE_MIMALLOC to USE_BUN_MIMALLOC to avoid conflicts with the updated WebKit's own macro definitions
Updated JSDOMPromiseDeferred.h template signatures to match new WebKit exception handling patterns (CatchScope → TopExceptionScope)
expertise_classifications.summary: Updates the vendored WebKit dependency to a new version that renamed CatchScope to TopExceptionScope and requires bmalloc linking, demonstrating deep understanding of WebKit internals and Bun's integration points across the entire codebase.

expertise_classifications.author: cirospaciari
expertise_signals: Introduced a new SocketMode enum to replace the boolean is_server flag, enabling a third 'duplex_server' mode that distinguishes listener-owned servers from duplex-upgraded TLS servers — a cross-cutting architectural change affecting socket lifecycle management
Deep understanding of TLS handshake direction (client vs server role) and how it interacts with ALPN negotiation, connection injection, and the uSockets/SSLWrapper layer
Created a new module (_http2_upgrade.ts) implementing HTTP/2 connection injection over upgraded duplex connections, handling complex protocol negotiation and connection lifecycle

Fixed SSLWrapper initialization (is_client parameter) and ensured markInactive uses client lifecycle path for duplex_server mode, showing understanding of subtle resource management differences between listener-owned and injected connections
expertise_classifications.summary: Introduces a new SocketMode abstraction replacing the boolean is_server flag to support duplex-to-TLS server upgrades, enables HTTP/2 connection injection into Http2SecureServer, and fixes SSLWrapper client/server role handling — demonstrating architect-level understanding of the TLS, socket lifecycle, and HTTP/2 subsystems.

expertise_classifications.author: robobun
expertise_signals: Changed pg_hba.conf from localhost-only (127.0.0.1/32, ::1/128) to container-accessible network ranges (0.0.0.0/0, ::/0) with added local socket trust rules for init scripts - understanding Docker networking constraints

Added 'local all postgres trust' and 'local all all trust' entries before remote rules, showing understanding that Postgres init scripts use local socket connections that would fail without these entries
Migrated from external secret-based TLS Postgres URLs to a container-based postgres_tls service with proper build step registration, eliminating CI secret dependencies
Increased health check start_period from 5s to 60s with 1s start_interval, accounting for the longer startup time of a custom-built container with SSL certificate generation
expertise_classifications.summary: Refactors TLS SQL tests from relying on external secret-based Postgres URLs to a locally-built Docker container, demonstrating deep understanding of Postgres authentication (pg_hba.conf ordering), Docker networking for containers, and health check tuning for custom builds.

expertise_classifications.author: cirospaciari
expertise_signals: Extracted isNoProxy into a reusable public function and applied it consistently across both fetch (Zig) and WebSocket (C++) codepaths, showing cross-cutting architectural awareness
Created a C FFI bridge (Bun__isNoProxy) to expose Zig logic to C++ WebSocket code, demonstrating understanding of the interop boundary between the two runtimes
Preserved the distinction between proxy:'' (explicitly no proxy) and proxy:URL (explicit proxy that should still respect NO_PROXY), showing careful understanding of the semantic contract
Added comprehensive test coverage for both fetch and WebSocket proxy bypass scenarios, including edge cases with NO_PROXY patterns
expertise_classifications.summary: Fixes NO_PROXY to be respected even when explicit proxy options are provided in both fetch and WebSocket, extracting a shared isNoProxy function and bridging it across the Zig/C++ boundary, demonstrating deep understanding of the proxy resolution semantics and the runtime's cross-language architecture.

expertise_classifications.author: alii
expertise_signals: Correctly threads the --retry flag through CLI parsing (cli.zig, Arguments.zig), config (bunfig.zig), and test execution (Execution.zig, ScopeFunctions.zig)
Modifies the Zig test runner's retry logic in Execution.zig and ScopeFunctions.zig, showing understanding of how test execution flows through the codebase
Adds JUnit XML emission for retry attempts as separate testcase entries, indicating awareness of reporting infrastructure
Comprehensive test coverage with 315-line retry-flag.test.ts and additional JUnit reporter tests
expertise_classifications.summary: Adds a --retry flag for test retries with full integration across CLI parsing, bunfig config, Zig test execution, JUnit XML reporting, completions, and documentation, demonstrating working-level understanding of the codebase's end-to-end feature plumbing.

expertise_classifications.author: Jarred-Sumner
expertise_signals: Designed a new multi_run.zig module (838 lines) integrating with Bun's process lifecycle, event loop, and workspace resolution from scratch
Extended ProcessExitHandler's tagged union to register a new MultiRunProcessHandle, showing deep understanding of the process management architecture
Integrated at the CLI dispatch level in cli.zig, correctly placing the parallel/sequential check before the existing filter_run path with proper exit handling
Comprehensive test suite (2023 lines) covering parallel, sequential, workspace filtering, glob matching, --if-present, --no-exit-on-error, and Foreman-style prefixed output
expertise_classifications.summary: Introduces a new parallel/sequential multi-script execution system with workspace support, requiring new process lifecycle integration, a new CLI module, and extensive cross-cutting changes that demonstrate system-level architectural ownership.

expertise_classifications.author: robobun
expertise_signals: Updating inline snapshots to match new Redis 8 error message format
Purely mechanical removal of trailing ', with args beginning with: ' from error strings
No logic changes, only string literal updates across 3 assertions
expertise_classifications.summary: Trivial test snapshot update to reflect a changed error message format in Redis 8, requiring no understanding of application logic.

expertise_classifications.author: sosukesuzuki
expertise_signals: Adds cycle/shared-reference detection via HashSet<JSObject*> seenObjects to correctly fall back when object identity can't be preserved in the fast path
Understands JSC internals deeply: butterfly contiguous data access, structure property table iteration, getDirect with offsets, and isObjectFastPathCandidate checks
Implements proper memory cost accounting for the new DenseArray variant using std::visit with WTF::makeVisitor over the variant types
Comprehensive test suite (516+ lines) covering edge cases like holes, symbols, BigInt, circular references, nested objects, and ensuring correct fallback to normal serialization
expertise_classifications.summary: Adds a DenseArray fast path to structuredClone that handles arrays containing simple objects (with primitive/string properties) by avoiding full serialization/deserialization, demonstrating deep understanding of JSC's object model, structure metadata, and the existing fast-path architecture.

expertise_classifications.author: prekucki
expertise_signals: Uses Symbol.for to persist state across HMR runtime reloads via globalThis, preventing loss of pending script references when the runtime itself is re-evaluated

Converts the script tracking from a simple map entry to a queue (array) per source map ID, correctly handling the race condition where multiple HMR updates for the same module arrive before prior ones are consumed

The test exercises rapid consecutive file edits (1ms apart) with error interception hooks on both 'error' and 'unhandledrejection' events, precisely targeting the race condition described in issue #19736
Wraps the original bun:hmr callback to catch and record errors without crashing, showing understanding of the async script loading pipeline and its failure modes
expertise_classifications.summary: Fixes a race condition where rapid consecutive HMR updates caused 'Unknown HMR script' errors by converting the script tag registry to a per-module queue and persisting it across runtime re-evaluations, demonstrating deep understanding of the HMR script loading pipeline and its timing edge cases.

expertise_classifications.author: dylan-conway
expertise_signals: Cross-compilation setup for Windows ARM64 from x64 runners with specific toolchain flags (--toolchain windows-aarch64, clang-cl, SKIP_CODEGEN)
C++ source fixes for LLVM 21 compatibility: updated std::optional usage, fixed implicit conversions, addressed stricter type checking in URLPatternParser, WebCoreTypedArrayController, and CPUFeatures
Removed workaround symbols that are no longer needed with LLVM 21 (workaround-missing-symbols.cpp cleanup)
Coordinated changes across CI infrastructure (Buildkite, GitHub Actions, Nix flakes, bootstrap scripts, CMake) showing understanding of the full build pipeline
expertise_classifications.summary: Upgrades the LLVM toolchain from 19.1.7 to 21.1.8 across the entire build infrastructure, fixes C++ source compatibility issues with the stricter compiler, enables Windows ARM64 cross-compilation, and updates Alpine/musl targets — demonstrating deep understanding of the build system, CI pipeline, and compiler behavior.

expertise_classifications.author: robobun
expertise_signals: Identified a missing reference count increment (incPendingActivityCount) in the Blob binaryType path that allows premature GC before an async postTask callback fires
Understands the GC lifecycle interaction with C++ prevent-GC ref counting (incPendingActivityCount pattern) - a subtle concurrency/lifetime bug
The test specifically targets the race condition: creating unreferenced WebSocket objects with blob binaryType, no listeners, and forced GC to reproduce 'Pure virtual function called!'
Recognizes that the arraybuffer/arraybufferview paths already had the incPendingActivityCount call but the blob path was missing it - showing careful comparison of parallel code paths
expertise_classifications.summary: Fixes a use-after-free crash in WebSocket's blob binaryType path by adding a missing incPendingActivityCount() call that prevents GC from collecting the WebSocket before its postTask callback runs, demonstrating deep understanding of the C++ GC prevent-destroy mechanism and async callback lifecycles.

expertise_classifications.author: sosukesuzuki
expertise_signals: Ported WebKit JSC JIT stress tests (DFG, FTL, WASM tiers) specifically targeting Bun's JavaScriptCore engine internals
Created a test harness (jsc-stress.test.ts + preload.js) that adapts WebKit's test infrastructure (e.g., shimming $vm helpers, noInline, etc.) to run under Bun's test runner
Carefully selected tests covering JIT compiler edge cases: OSR entry/exit, register allocation, try-catch recovery, tail calls, WASM tier-up scenarios
Included bunfig.toml with preload configuration and proper LICENSE attribution for WebKit-derived test code
expertise_classifications.summary: Ports ~80 WebKit JSC JIT stress tests covering DFG, FTL, and WASM compiler tiers into Bun's test suite with a custom harness, demonstrating deep understanding of JSC's JIT compilation pipeline and the specific edge cases that matter for Bun's fork.

expertise_classifications.author: dylan-conway
expertise_signals: Chose specific CPU models (Nehalem for x64 baseline with SSE4.2, Cortex-A53 for ARMv8.0-A) that precisely match the project's baseline CPU targets, showing understanding of ISA feature levels
Used QEMU user-mode emulation rather than full system emulation for lightweight CI verification - a non-obvious approach to catch illegal instructions at build time
Handles both static and dynamic QEMU binaries with fallback, and distinguishes SIGILL (exit 132) from other failures with specific diagnostic messages per architecture
Integrated the verification step into the existing CI pipeline with proper dependency chaining, artifact naming conventions, and conditional application only to platforms that need it
expertise_classifications.summary: Adds QEMU user-mode emulation CI steps to verify baseline CPU builds don't contain privileged instructions (AVX/AVX2 on x64, LSE/SVE on aarch64), demonstrating deep understanding of CPU ISA feature tiers and cross-architecture build verification strategies.

expertise_classifications.author: robobun
expertise_signals: Identifies HTTP header injection vulnerability via CRLF in user-controlled header values (contentDisposition, contentType, contentEncoding)
Validates at the correct layer - input parsing in credentials.zig before values are used in HTTP headers
Comprehensive test coverage including CRLF, CR-only, LF-only, and valid value cases
Positive test case verifies valid values still work by checking a request is actually sent to a mock server
expertise_classifications.summary: Security fix rejecting CRLF characters in S3 header values to prevent HTTP header injection, with thorough input validation at the parsing layer and comprehensive regression tests covering all edge cases.

expertise_classifications.author: dylan-conway
expertise_signals: Handles cross-compilation edge cases like using Hostx64/arm64 linker paths vs HostARM64/arm64 with fallback logic for MSVC toolchain discovery
Understands that ARM64 atomics are lock-free and pre-sets cache variables to avoid cross-compile test failures (highway's FindAtomics can't run ARM64 binaries on x64)
Correctly disables BoringSSL ASM to avoid mixing non-ARM object files into ARM64 libs, and adds cargo --target for lolhtml cross-compilation

Guards post-build test/feature steps with CMAKE_CROSSCOMPILING to avoid running target binaries on the host, and restructures the toolchain file to separate Windows-specific settings from Zig cross-compile needs
expertise_classifications.summary: Fixes Windows ARM64 cross-compilation CI by reworking the CMake toolchain, correcting MSVC/linker discovery for cross-compile scenarios, disabling incompatible ASM, and guarding host-only build steps — demonstrating deep knowledge of CMake cross-compilation mechanics, MSVC toolchain layout, and multiple build subsystems.

expertise_classifications.author: robobun
expertise_signals: Updated root certificates from NSS to version 3.119, removing revoked/distrusted CommScope and Globalsign certificates
Systematically replaced external HTTPS endpoints in tests with localhost/internal alternatives to improve test reliability
Modified multiple test files across different modules (fetch, http, http2, sqlite, shell) to eliminate external network dependencies
Understanding of test infrastructure concerns - replacing flaky external calls (e.g., example.com, httpbin.org) with local servers or appropriate alternatives
expertise_classifications.summary: Updates NSS root certificates to 3.119 (removing distrusted CAs) and replaces external HTTPS calls in tests with local alternatives, showing working knowledge of both TLS certificate management and test reliability concerns.

expertise_classifications.author: Jarred-Sumner
expertise_signals: Designed and implemented a complete TC39 standard ES decorators lowering pass (~1500 lines in lowerDecorators.zig), including handling of private fields, auto-accessors, method/getter/setter decorators, and class decorators with proper initialization ordering

Integrated the new lowering across the entire compilation pipeline: parser, visitor, printer, bundler, module loader, runtime, and tsconfig resolution - showing deep understanding of the full transpiler architecture
Created a dedicated runtime support module (src/runtime.js additions) with helper functions (__esDecorate, __esRunInitializers, __esRunDecorators) that implement the TC39 decorator protocol correctly

Handled nuanced edge cases like anonymous decorated class expressions needing name propagation via decorator_class_name, private member lowering with storage refs, and interaction with TypeScript experimental decorators vs standard decorators
expertise_classifications.summary: Implements complete TC39 standard ES decorators lowering from scratch, touching parser, visitor, printer, bundler, runtime, and resolver modules with ~6700 lines added, demonstrating architect-level understanding of the transpiler's end-to-end compilation pipeline and the TC39 decorators specification.

expertise_classifications.author: dylan-conway
expertise_signals: Identified a use-after-free caused by an asymmetric counter increment: output_waiting was only incremented in the async (needsIO) path but output_done was always incremented, causing premature done()/free when stdout is synchronous (e.g., inside command substitution)
The fix moves the increment of output_waiting before the needsIO check so both sync and async paths keep counters balanced — a subtle concurrency/lifetime invariant
Applied the same fix consistently across all four affected builtins (cp, ls, mkdir, touch), showing awareness of the shared OutputTask pattern
Regression test specifically targets the ASAN use-after-poison scenario with command substitution and many error-producing ls tasks, demonstrating understanding of the exact failure mode
expertise_classifications.summary: Fixes a use-after-free in shell builtin OutputTask callbacks by moving the output_waiting counter increment before the needsIO branch, ensuring the counter is balanced for both sync and async write paths — demonstrating deep understanding of the lifetime and concurrency invariants in the shell execution pipeline.

expertise_classifications.author: sosukesuzuki
expertise_signals: Understands JIT compilation tiers (DFG, FTL, Wasm BBQ/OMG) and their instruction generation implications for baseline CPU targets
Carefully distinguishes SIGILL (exit code 132) from other failures, treating only CPU instruction issues as hard failures
Selects precise CPU models (Nehalem for SSE4.2-no-AVX, Cortex-A53 for ARMv8.0-A+CRC-no-LSE) matching the project's baseline targets
Conditionally triggers the expensive QEMU test only when SetupWebKit.cmake changes, showing understanding of when JIT regressions can be introduced
expertise_classifications.summary: Adds QEMU-based JIT stress testing to CI that detects when WebKit updates introduce JIT-compiled code using CPU instructions beyond baseline targets, demonstrating deep understanding of JIT compilation tiers, CPU instruction set boundaries, and targeted CI optimization.

expertise_classifications.author: Jarred-Sumner
expertise_signals: Designed and implemented an entire Markdown parser from scratch in Zig (13+ new files in src/md/) covering blocks, inlines, containers, autolinks, entity resolution, unicode handling, and reference definitions
Created full integration across the Zig-JS boundary: MarkdownObject.zig bindings, JSReactElement C++ bindings, ModuleLoader integration for .md imports, and transpiler/bundler support
Designed three distinct rendering APIs (HTML, custom callbacks, React JSX) with proper JSC/JavaScriptCore interop including custom JSReactElement C++ class for efficient React element creation
Comprehensive GFM specification compliance with dedicated spec test files, edge case tests, regression tracking, and coverage documentation spanning ~10k+ lines of test fixtures
expertise_classifications.summary: Implements a complete Markdown parser and rendering engine in Zig with full GFM support, three rendering modes (HTML/callback/React), JS bindings, bundler integration, and extensive spec-level testing — a system-level feature addition that defines a new module and its cross-cutting integration points.

expertise_classifications.author: robobun
expertise_signals: Handles edge cases where chunk terminators (\r\n) are split across TCP packet boundaries, with separate validation logic for remaining=0,1,2 and >2 bytes
Validates terminator bytes incrementally in the partial-read path (else branch) to prevent request smuggling even when data arrives fragmented
Uses switch with fallthrough to elegantly handle the multiple terminator validation states in the complete-data path
Tests specifically target fragmented chunk terminators split across socket writes with timing delays, demonstrating understanding of real-world TCP framing issues
expertise_classifications.summary: Hardens the chunked encoding parser to correctly validate \r\n terminators when they are split across TCP read boundaries, preventing potential request smuggling — demonstrating deep understanding of HTTP parsing edge cases and streaming protocol correctness.

expertise_classifications.author: robobun
expertise_signals: Replaces a polling loop with an event-driven approach to eliminate race conditions causing flaky tests
Handles already-buffered messages before subscribing to new ones, preventing a subtle race where the target message arrives before the listener is attached
Understands HMR watcher coalescing behavior (intermediate renders may be skipped) and duplicate reload semantics
Properly cleans up event listeners on both success and error paths to avoid leaks or double-resolution
expertise_classifications.summary: Converts a flaky HMR test from a sequential polling loop to an event-driven wait pattern that correctly handles buffered messages, coalesced renders, and duplicate reloads, showing understanding of the async race conditions that caused test flakiness.

expertise_classifications.author: robobun
expertise_signals: Understands that null bytes act as field terminators in both MySQL and PostgreSQL wire protocols, enabling parameter injection attacks
Properly cleans up allocated resources (options_buf, tls_config, tls_ctx) before returning errors to prevent memory leaks
Uses Zig's `inline for` with comptime string concatenation for DRY validation across multiple parameters
Tests verify not just error messages but that no data reaches the server (validating rejection happens before connection), and includes a negative test showing normal connections still work
expertise_classifications.summary: Fixes a protocol injection vulnerability by rejecting null bytes in SQL connection parameters before they reach the wire protocol, demonstrating understanding of wire protocol internals, resource cleanup patterns in the codebase, and thorough security-oriented testing.

expertise_classifications.author: alii
expertise_signals: Introduces a new ESM bytecode compilation pipeline spanning 37 files across bundler, runtime, standalone module graph, transpiler cache, and C++ bindings - demonstrating deep system-level understanding
Created analyze_transpiled_module.zig (513 lines) implementing bytecode-compatible module analysis with careful handling of import/export metadata serialization for V8/JSC bytecode caching
Modified postProcessJSChunk.zig and generateChunksInParallel.zig to thread module_info through the chunk generation pipeline, showing understanding of the bundler's multi-phase architecture

Handles bytecode alignment constraints (256-byte alignment in StandaloneModuleGraph), bytecode_origin_path matching for cache hits, and integrates with both RuntimeTranspilerCache and standalone compilation - showing awareness of multiple runtime execution contexts
expertise_classifications.summary: Implements ESM bytecode compilation support across the entire pipeline—bundler, runtime module loader, standalone module graph, transpiler cache, and C++ bindings—introducing a new module_info metadata format and bytecode origin path tracking, demonstrating architect-level understanding of Bun's compilation and execution architecture.

expertise_classifications.author: robobun
expertise_signals: Created a new 731-line MetafileBuilder.zig module that generates structured markdown analysis from bundle metadata, showing understanding of the bundler's internal data structures (LinkerContext, SourceIndex, chunks, parts)

Extended the metafile API across multiple layers: CLI arguments, JS API (supporting boolean | string | object overloads), Zig bundler options, linker context, and C++ bindings - demonstrating cross-cutting system knowledge

Properly handled output artifact classification (metafile-json, metafile-markdown) with correct standalone mode exclusion via isFileInStandaloneMode, showing awareness of how artifacts flow through the build pipeline
Wrote 722 lines of integration tests covering CLI flags, JS API variants (boolean, string, object), markdown output validation, and edge cases like empty bundles and CSS-only bundles
expertise_classifications.summary: Adds a comprehensive --metafile-md feature that generates LLM-friendly markdown bundle analysis, touching the CLI layer, JS API, bundler linker context, C++ bindings, and build artifact pipeline with a new MetafileBuilder module, demonstrating deep understanding of the bundler's architecture and data flow.

pattern_result.executive_summary: Bun's human code review is effectively non-existent—every human reviewer (including project lead Jarred Sumner) rubber-stamps PRs, with all substantive review coming from the coderabbitai bot. Critical knowledge drain is occurring in src/bundler (59% owner zackradisic absent) and src/bun.js (25% owner paperclover absent). The team has strong individual experts but zero structured knowledge transfer between them.

insights.title: Every human review is a rubber stamp — bots are the only real reviewers
insights.description: Across all 99 PRs analyzed, not a single human reviewer provided substantive feedback. Jarred-Sumner rubber-stamped PRs #26441, #26439, #26440, #26380, #26539, #26402 (all architect/deep-level, highly complex changes). Dylan-Conway rubber-stamped PRs #26878, #26440, #26551. Alii rubber-stamped PRs #23995, #26439, #26402 (including their own). Ciro rubber-stamped PR #26410 (their own area). The only thorough reviews come from coderabbitai. This means no human is verifying correctness or transferring knowledge on any PR in the project.

insights.title: src/bundler's majority owner zackradisic has vanished — zero commits in 3 months
insights.description: zackradisic (56137411+zackradisic@users.noreply.github.com) holds 59% blame ownership of src/bundler but does not appear in the last 3 months of contributor data at all. Jarred Sumner holds only 15% and paperclover 11% (also absent). The bus factor of 0.20 reflects this fragility. Jarred's recent bundler-adjacent work (decorators PR#26436, markdown PR#26440) is adding new features but the core bundler linker/resolver knowledge may be walking out the door.

insights.title: paperclover holds 25% of src/bun.js and 11% of src/bundler but has disappeared
insights.description: git@paperclover.net is the second-largest owner of src/bun.js (25% blame across 1060 commits) and holds 11% of src/bundler, but has zero commits in the last 3 months. Combined with zackradisic's absence from src/bundler, two of the three historically dominant contributors to Bun's two largest modules are no longer active. The institutional knowledge loss is compounding.

insights.title: src/ast has a 95% single-owner bus factor with a low-activity contributor
insights.description: pfg@pfg.pw owns 95% of src/ast blame but has only 3 commits in the last 3 months (one being a large build.zig change). The remaining 5% is split between contact@taylor.fish (2%) and zackradisic (2%, also absent). Alistair Smith (alii) is now active in src/ast but from the ownership data hasn't yet built significant blame share. If pfg leaves, the AST module — foundational to the parser, bundler, and transpiler — would have no knowledgeable maintainer.

insights.title: Security-critical PRs reviewed only by bots that rubber-stamp
insights.description: PR#26594 (chunked encoding parser hardening to prevent request smuggling) received SEVEN reviews from 'claude' — all empty rubber stamps. PR#26952 (SQL null byte injection fix) and PR#26942 (S3 CRLF header injection fix) show no human security review in the data. The project's security posture depends entirely on the PR author catching their own mistakes, since no human reviews security-sensitive code and the 'claude' bot integration appears to produce only empty comments.

insights.title: Ciro Spaciari is the sole architect of the networking stack with no backup
insights.description: Ciro (ciro.spaciari@gmail.com) owns 8% of src/bun.js and is responsible for all architect-level networking changes: TLS socket mode abstraction (PR#26539), HTTP/2 server upgrades, proxy bypass logic (PR#26608), HTTP parser tunnel fix (PR#26737). He works across packages/bun-uws, src/bun.js, and src/js. No other contributor touches HTTP/2, TLS, or proxy code. His PRs are either self-approved or rubber-stamped by Jarred Sumner with no comments.

insights.title: Alistair Smith is an emerging architect with unusually high-impact per commit
insights.description: Alii has only 18 commits but delivered PR#26402 (ESM bytecode compilation) — rated architect-level, highly complex — touching bundler, runtime module loader, standalone module graph, transpiler cache, and C++ bindings. His 4987 lines added vs 18 commits ratio (277 lines/commit) and his spread across src/OutputFile.zig, src/StandaloneModuleGraph.zig, src/analyze_transpiled_module.zig, src/ast, and src/bake shows he's building cross-cutting architectural knowledge. He's the most promising candidate to backfill knowledge gaps in src/bundler and src/ast.

insights.title: Dylan Conway is the team's best cross-pollinator but stuck in infrastructure
insights.description: Dylan bridges more domains than anyone else: shell runtime (src/shell), WebKit vendoring (PR#26381), LLVM toolchain upgrades (PR#26667), QEMU CPU verification (PR#26571), Windows ARM64 cross-compilation (PR#26703), JSON5 parser (PR#26439), and cmake/tools (59% ownership). He has deep+architect expertise across build systems and runtime code. His breadth makes him the best candidate for knowledge transfer sessions, but his time appears consumed by infrastructure/toolchain work that doesn't grow product knowledge in others.

insights.title: SUZUKI Sosuke is building a JSC performance specialization no one else shares
insights.description: Sosuke has carved out a unique niche: Buffer.slice native fast path (PR#26819), structuredClone DenseArray optimization (PR#26818), JIT stress test porting from WebKit (PR#26380), and QEMU JIT stress CI (PR#26589). All four PRs demonstrate deep JSC VM internals knowledge (DFG/FTL tiers, TypedArray semantics, structure metadata). No other contributor works at this layer. With 30 commits and 14588 lines added, he's productive but creating an isolated knowledge silo in JSC performance internals.

insights.title: Przemysław Rekucki — external Anthropic contributor with deep HMR knowledge
insights.description: prekucki (email: alistair@anthropic.com) has only 4 commits but PR#23995 fixed a subtle HMR race condition involving per-module script queuing and persistence across runtime re-evaluations. This is deep knowledge of a system that otherwise only paperclover (absent) and Jarred would understand. His low commit count but high-complexity contributions across completions, bunfig, CLI, and HMR suggest he's an external power-user who understands internals better than most team members.

recommendations: Institute mandatory human review with written comments for all PRs touching src/bundler, src/ast, networking, and security-sensitive code — the current all-rubber-stamp culture means zero knowledge transfer.
Pair Alistair Smith with Jarred Sumner on src/bundler work immediately — zackradisic and paperclover's combined 70% ownership is unrecoverable if not transferred now.

Require Ciro Spaciari to document the networking architecture (TLS, HTTP/2, proxy) and have Dylan Conway or Sosuke review his PRs substantively — he's a single point of failure for the entire network stack.
Audit the 'claude' bot integration — it produced 12+ empty rubber-stamp reviews including on security-critical PRs, providing false review coverage signals.
Have SUZUKI Sosuke run a JSC internals knowledge-sharing session for the team — his DFG/FTL/TypedArray expertise exists nowhere else in the org.
Actively recruit pfg for deeper src/ast engagement or assign alii to build blame share — 95% single-owner on the AST module is one resignation away from crisis.
Create written onboarding docs for src/bundler using git blame archaeology before institutional knowledge of zackradisic's 59% ownership becomes permanently inaccessible.
